To all the people who say the terminology is unnecessary. First, the anatomical directions are conventional for ALL organisms, not just humans. So when I define a cranio-caudal axis it could stand for an vertical axis in humans but for a horizontal axis for a quadruped or a laying human. "Cranio" means skull and "caudal" means tail, which are two invariable points in anatomy. If a person is lying on his back cranial would mean to the left or to the right depending on where you are standing in regard to the person as the axis is horizontal. The same goes with caudal. Take for example the planes. How are you going to call them if not by their conventional names? In standing position the hand would be the superior member, the leg would be the inferior, the same goes in dorsal decubitus (that's when the patient is on his back). If you'd call superior - high and inferior - low, in laying position, the hand cannot be described as "higher" than the leg or the leg "lower" than the hand. It just doesn't make sense. Then you have what's called lateral and medial which cannot be substituted with right and left, because left and right depends on the direction you are facing, but medial is always medial and lateral is always lateral. The utility of these terms comes from the fact that in anatomy the subject is the spatial reference for himself, whereas when you use traditional directions like right, left, up, down, etc, you do it using yourself as a referential. 
Imagine a cut that's going vertically in the sagittal plane through a nasal cavity, which has a medial and a lateral wall. You cannot call the lateral wall the left or the right wall because you can cut through the right or the left nasal cavity, and directions would always have to change. Lateral wall would mean the left wall for the left cavity and the right wall for the right cavity, whereas left wall for the right cavity would be medial. So if I define the human body as an absolute referential I do not care if the body is standing, on the back, on his right or left side, or sitting.

I'm sure you ran out of time to cover this but there's a reason for having two terms for most of the directional words. Some of them change a bit when talking about the anatomy of non bipedal animals. For example human backs are posterior and dorsal but when talking about a cat or other four legged animals their backs are superior and dorsal. A more accurate description of these terms is anterior=front, ventral=chest, posterior=behind, dorsal=back, superior=above, cranial=head, inferior=below, caudal=tail. Pretty much the ones ending in -al are specific to the body areas while the ones ending in -or are more general definitions that sound like they could describe even a car. Good introduction though!
